    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The surface of the snowpack has frozen to form a strong crust only at high altitudes and will soften during the day. Faceted weak layers exist in the bottom section of the snowpack on steep shady slopes.</highlights>
      <comment>The avalanche prone locations for dry avalanches are to be found on steep shady slopes above approximately 2800 m. &lt;br/> As a consequence of warming during the day and the solar radiation, the likelihood of wet avalanches being released will increase in particular on steep shady slopes below approximately 2800 m. &lt;br/> Medium-sized avalanches are possible.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>The surface of the snowpack will soften during the day. &lt;br/> Steep shady slopes above approximately 2800 m: Faceted weak layers exist in the bottom section of the old snowpack. &lt;br/> Below approximately 2100 m from a snow sport perspective, in most cases insufficient snow is lying.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
